  "prompt": "What is the meaning of f(2) in calculus?",
  "response": "In calculus, \\( f(2) \\) typically represents the value of the function \\( f \\) at the point where the input (or independent variable) is 2. Essentially, it tells you what output the function \\( f \\) produces when 2 is substituted into it. If \\( f(x) \\) is a rule that maps inputs to outputs, then \\( f(2) \\) is specifically the output when the input is 2. This is part of evaluating functions, a basic operation in calculus and algebra.",
